# CSS Text Properties

CSS text properties are used to control the appearance and formatting of text on a webpage.

---

## 1. `font-size`

Sets the size of the text.

**Example:**

```css
p {
  font-size: 18px;
}
```

---

## 2. `font-family`

Specifies the font (typeface) of the text.

**Example:**

```css
body {
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}
```

---

## 3. `font-style`

Changes the style of the text.

**Common Values:**

- `normal`
- `italic`
- `oblique`

**Example:**

```css
p {
  font-style: italic;
}
```

---

## 4. `text-transform`

Changes the capitalization of text.

**Common Values:**

- `uppercase` → ALL CAPITAL LETTERS
- `lowercase` → all small letters
- `capitalize` → First Letter Of Each Word
- `none` → Default text

**Example:**

```css
h1 {
  text-transform: uppercase;
}
```

---

## 5. `text-align`

Aligns text horizontally.

**Common Values:**

- `left`
- `center`
- `right`
- `justify`

**Example:**

```css
h1 {
  text-align: center;
}
```

---

## 6. `line-height`

Controls the vertical space between lines of text.

**Example:**

```css
p {
  line-height: 1.6;
}
```

---

## 7. `font-weight`

Controls the thickness (boldness) of the text.

**Common Values:**

- `normal`
- `bold`
- `100` to `900`

**Example:**

```css
h1 {
  font-weight: bold;
}
```

---

## 8. `list-style`

Changes the appearance of list markers.

**Common Values:**

- `disc`
- `circle`
- `square`
- `none`

**Example:**

```css
ul {
  list-style: square;
}
```

To remove bullets:

```css
ul {
  list-style: none;
}
```

---

# Summary Table

| Property         | Purpose                                            |
| ---------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |
| `font-size`      | Sets the text size.                                |
| `font-family`    | Specifies the font.                                |
| `font-style`     | Changes the text style (normal, italic).           |
| `text-transform` | Changes letter capitalization.                     |
| `text-align`     | Aligns the text.                                   |
| `line-height`    | Sets the space between lines.                      |
| `font-weight`    | Controls the boldness of the text.                 |
| `list-style`     | Changes or removes list markers (bullets/numbers). |

---

# Key Points

- Use **`font-size`** to control text size.
- Use **`font-family`** to choose a font.
- Use **`font-style`** for italic or oblique text.
- Use **`text-transform`** to change letter casing.
- Use **`text-align`** to align text.
- Use **`line-height`** to improve readability.
- Use **`font-weight`** to make text lighter or bolder.
- Use **`list-style`** to customize or remove list bullets and numbering.

# Combining Selectors

**Combining selectors** allows you to apply the same style to multiple elements or to select elements based on their relationship.

---

## 1. List Selector (Grouping Selector)

A **list selector** is used to apply the **same CSS styles to multiple elements**.

Instead of writing separate CSS rules, you can group selectors using a **comma (`,`)**.

### Syntax

```css id="7a2u7l"
selector1,
selector2,
selector3 {
  property: value;
}
```

### Example

```css id="5ik1rd"
h1,
h2,
p {
  color: blue;
}
```

This applies the same text color (**blue**) to all `<h1>`, `<h2>`, and `<p>` elements.

### Why Use It?

- Reduces duplicate code.
- Makes CSS cleaner and easier to maintain.

---

## 2. Descendant Selector

A **descendant selector** selects an element that is **inside another element**, regardless of how deeply it is nested.

It uses a **space** between the selectors.

### Syntax

```css id="opzm50"
parent child {
  property: value;
}
```

### Example

#### HTML

```html id="xrlm5e"
<article>
  <p>This paragraph is inside an article.</p>
</article>

<p>This paragraph is outside the article.</p>
```

#### CSS

```css id="jlwm4m"
article p {
  color: red;
}
```

### Result

- ✅ The paragraph **inside** `<article>` becomes **red**.
- ❌ The paragraph **outside** `<article>` is **not affected**.

### Why Use It?

Use a descendant selector when you want to style elements **only within a specific parent element**.

---

# Quick Reference

| Selector                | Syntax          | Purpose                                         |
| ----------------------- | --------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| **List Selector**       | `h1, h2, p { }` | Applies the same styles to multiple elements.   |
| **Descendant Selector** | `article p { }` | Selects child elements inside a parent element. |

---

# Key Points

- **List Selector (`,`)** → Styles multiple elements using one CSS rule.
- **Descendant Selector (space)** → Styles elements that are inside another element.
- Group selectors with a **comma**.
- Select descendants using a **space** between selectors.

Class & ID Selector

# CSS Selectors

A **CSS Selector** is used to select HTML elements so that you can apply styles to them.

---

## 1. Class Selector (`.`)

A **class selector** is used to style **one or more HTML elements** that share the same class name.

### HTML

```html id="kzvk80"
<h1 class="heading">Welcome</h1>

<p class="heading">Hello World!</p>
```

### CSS

```css id="1g9jti"
.heading {
  color: blue;
}
```

**Output:**

- Both the `<h1>` and `<p>` elements become **blue** because they have the same class.

---

# 2. ID Selector (`#`)

An **ID selector** is used to style **one unique HTML element**.

### HTML

```html id="ewcqz5"
<h1 id="title">Welcome</h1>
```

### CSS

```css id="ylv0jh"
#title {
  color: red;
}
```

Only the element with `id="title"` will be styled.

---

# Difference Between `class` and `id`

| Class (`class`)                  | ID (`id`)                                                       |
| -------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Starts with `.` in CSS           | Starts with `#` in CSS                                          |
| Can be used on multiple elements | Should be used only once per page                               |
| Reusable                         | Unique                                                          |
| Best for styling                 | Mainly used for unique elements, JavaScript, or page navigation |

---

# Why Use `class` Instead of `id` for CSS?

In modern web development, **classes are preferred for styling**.

### Reasons

### 1. Reusable

One class can be applied to many elements.

```html id="e57bgx"
<h2 class="heading">HTML</h2>

<h2 class="heading">CSS</h2>

<h2 class="heading">JavaScript</h2>
```

```css id="6z5gfe"
.heading {
  color: blue;
}
```

All three headings use the same CSS.

---

### 2. Easier to Maintain

If you want to change the style later, update **one class** instead of multiple IDs.

---

### 3. Better for Large Projects

Large websites often have hundreds of elements with the same design. Classes allow you to reuse styles instead of writing duplicate CSS.

---

### 4. IDs Have Higher Specificity

An ID selector (`#`) has a higher priority than a class selector (`.`).

This can make your CSS harder to override and maintain.

Example:

```css id="i2t02j"
.heading {
  color: blue;
}

#title {
  color: red;
}
```

If an element has both:

```html id="m5k8y8"
<h1 id="title" class="heading">Hello</h1>
```

The text will be **red** because the ID selector has higher specificity.

---

# When to Use `id`

Use an `id` when the element is **unique** on the page.

Examples:

- Main navigation
- Hero section
- Login form
- Unique banner

It is also commonly used for:

- JavaScript (`document.getElementById()`)
- Linking to a section of a page

Example:

```html id="g4q0ps"
<section id="about">...</section>

<a href="#about">Go to About Section</a>
```

---

# When to Use `class`

Use a `class` whenever you want to:

- Style multiple elements.
- Reuse the same styles.
- Build scalable and maintainable CSS.

---

# Key Points

- `.` → Class Selector
- `#` → ID Selector
- A **class** can be reused on multiple elements.
- An **ID** should be unique on a webpage.
- **Use classes for CSS styling.**
- **Use IDs for unique elements, JavaScript, or anchor links.**
